    <Descriptive_Notes>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Name given to the bosses on large stretchers linking and strengthening the legs of a table or secretaire; often very richly carved and pierced.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>English</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000000/VP</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000121571/Watson, Wrightsman Collection (1966-1973)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Naam die wordt gegeven aan de knoppen op dwarshouten die de poten van een tafel of secretaire met elkaar verbinden en versterken. Vaak zijn ze rijkelijk versierd met snijwerk en doorboord.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Dutch</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000205/AAT-Ned</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000113770/AAT-Ned (1994-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>大型橫檔上的圓形突起物，連接並支撐桌腿或寫字台柱腿，多半刻鑿有繁複花樣。</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Chinese (traditional)</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
